{"title_page": "Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize", "text_new": "The '''Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize''' is an award given by the [[IEEE Control Systems Society]] (CSS) to recognize distinguished contributions to control systems science or engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ieeecss.org/awards/ieee-css-hendrik-w-bode-lecture-prize|title=IEEE CSS Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize|publisher=[[IEEE Control Systems Society]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> It was established in 1989, named after [[Hendrik Wade Bode|Hendrik W. Bode]] (1905\u20131982), a pioneer of modern control theory and system engineering, who revolutionized both the content and methodology of his chosen fields of research during his long career at [[Bell Labs]] and [[Harvard University]]. \n\nThe recipient of the award gives a plenary lecture at the annual IEEE Conference on Decision and Control (CDC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ieeecss-oll.org/category/lecture-type/bode-lecture|title=Bode Lecture|publisher=IEEE Control Systems Society Online Lecture Library |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> The inaugural Bode Prize Lecture was delivered by Gunter Stein at the 28th IEEE CDC in Tampa, Florida, on December 15, 1989.<ref name=stein>{{cite web|url=https://ethw.org/Archives:Respect_the_Unstable|title=Archives: Respect the Unstable (Video)|publisher=[[Engineering and Technology History Wiki]]|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recipients==\n{{colbegin}}\n* 1989: Gunter Stein<ref name=stein/>\n* 1990: [[David Luenberger]]\n* 1991: [[Petar V. Kokotovic]]\n* 1992: [[Brian Anderson (academic)|Brian D.O. Anderson]]\n* 1993: [[Michael Athans]]\n* 1994: [[Gene F. Franklin]]\n* 1995: [[Kumpati S. Narendra]]\n* 1996: Jurgen Ackermann<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ei.tum.de/lsr/team/lsr-alumni/juergen-ackermann/|title=J\u00fcrgen Ackermann|website=tum.de|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1997: Edward J. Davison<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ece.utoronto.ca/people/davison-e-j/|title=Davison E J|website=utoronto.ca|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.control.utoronto.ca/people/profs/ted/bio.html|title=Biography|website=utoronto.ca||accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1998: J. Boyd Pearson<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?arnumber=6516711|title=James Boyd Pearson [Obituary]|author=Munther A. Dahleh|journal=IEEE Control Systems Magazine|date=June 2013|volume=33|issue=3|pages=92\u2013 93|doi= 10.1109/MCS.2013.2249953|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1999: [[Graham Goodwin|Graham C. Goodwin]]\n* 2000: [[Mathukumalli Vidyasagar]]\n* 2001: [[Alberto Isidori]]\n* 2002: [[Eduardo D. Sontag]]\n* 2003: [[Lennart Ljung (engineer)|Lennart Ljung]]\n* 2004: [[Tamer Ba\u015far]]\n* 2005: [[Pravin Varaiya]]\n* 2006: [[Arthur J. Krener]]\n* 2007: [[P. S. Krishnaprasad]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isr.umd.edu/news/story/ps-krishnaprasad-gives-bode-lecture|title=P.S. Krishnaprasad gives Bode Lecture|website=umd.edu|date=10 December 2007}}</ref>\n* 2008: Christopher Byrnes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.ttu.edu/~gilliam/ttu/cib_mem_webpage/Chris_Byrnes_Workshop/Workshop.html|title=Workshop in Celebration of the Life, Mathematics and Memories of Christopher I. Byrnes|website=ttu.edu|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://source.wustl.edu/2010/02/chris-byrnes-former-dean-of-engineering-dies-at-60/|title=Chris Byrnes, former dean of engineering, dies at 60|website=wustl.edu|date=14 February 2010}}</ref>\n* 2009: [[Peter E. Caines]]\n* 2010: [[Manfred Morari]]\n* 2011: [[John Baillieul]]\n* 2012: Jessy W. Grizzle<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eecs.umich.edu/eecs/about/articles/2011/Grizzle-BodeLecturePrize.html|title=Prof. Jessy Grizzle Honored with Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize from IEEE Control Systems Society|website=umich.edu|date=19 December 2011}}</ref>\n* 2013: B. Ross Barmish<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?arnumber=6479387|title=The recipient of the 2013 Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize is Ross B. Barmish of the University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|journal=IEEE Control Systems Magazine|date=April 2013|volume=33|issue=2|pages=16|doi=10.1109/MCS.2012.2234928|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2014: Bruce Francis<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ece.utoronto.ca/news/francis-hendrik-bode-lecture-prize/|title=Bruce Francis awarded 2014 Hendrik Bode Lecture Prize|website=utoronto.ca|date=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n* 2015: Hassan Khalil<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ece.msu.edu/news/hendrick-w-bode-lecture-prize-khalil|title=Hendrick W. Bode Lecture Prize to Khalil|website=msu.edu|date=31 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[Richard M. Murray]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?tp=&arnumber=7823057|title=2016 IEEE CSS Awards|journal=IEEE Control Systems Magazine|date=February 2017 |volume=37|issue=1|pages=133|doi=10.1109/MCS.2016.2621466|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2017: [[Naomi Ehrich Leonard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isr.umd.edu/news/story/alumna-naomi-leonard-wins-hendrik-w-bode-lecture-prize|title=Alumna Naomi Leonard wins Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize|website=umd.edu|date=16 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 2018: [[Mark W. Spong]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://engineering.utdallas.edu/news/archive/2018-spring/spong-to-receive-prestigious-bode-lecture-prize/|title=Spong to Receive Prestigious Bode Lecture Prize|website=utdallas.edu|date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n* 2019: {{ill|Lei Guo|zh|\u90ed\u96f7}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lsc.amss.ac.cn/~lguo/prizes.html|title=Prizes and Honors |website=lsc.amss.ac.cn}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n* [[IEEE Control Systems Award]]\n* [[Giorgio Quazza Medal]]\n* [[Richard E. Bellman Control Heritage Award]]\n* [[Rufus Oldenburger Medal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Systems sciences awards]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize''' is an award given by the [[IEEE Control Systems Society]] to recognize distinguished contributions to control systems science or engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ieeecss.org/awards/ieee-css-hendrik-w-bode-lecture-prize|title=IEEE CSS Hendrik W. Bode Lecture Prize|publisher=[[IEEE Control Systems Society]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> It was established in 1989, named after [[Hendrik Wade Bode|Hendrik W. Bode]] (1905\u20131982), a pioneer of modern control theory and system engineering, who revolutionized both the content and methodology of his chosen fields of research during his long career at [[Bell Labs]] and [[Harvard University]]. \n\nThe recipient of the award gives a plenary lecture at the annual IEEE Conference on Decision and Control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ieeecss-oll.org/category/lecture-type/bode-lecture|title=Bode Lecture|publisher=IEEE Control Systems Society Online Lecture Library |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> The inaugural Bode Prize Lecture was delivered by Gunter Stein at the 28th IEEE CDC in Tampa, Florida, on December 15, 1989.<ref name=stein>{{cite web|url=https://ethw.org/Archives:Respect_the_Unstable|title=Archives: Respect the Unstable (Video)|publisher=[[Engineering and Technology History Wiki]]|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recipients==\n{{colbegin}}\n* 1989: Gunter Stein<ref name=stein/>\n* 1990: [[David Luenberger]]\n* 1991: [[Petar V. Kokotovic]]\n* 1992: [[Brian Anderson (academic)|Brian D.O. Anderson]]\n* 1993: [[Michael Athans]]\n* 1994: [[Gene F. Franklin]]\n* 1995: [[Kumpati S. Narendra]]\n* 1996: Jurgen Ackermann<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ei.tum.de/lsr/team/lsr-alumni/juergen-ackermann/|title=J\u00fcrgen Ackermann|website=tum.de|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1997: Edward J. Davison<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ece.utoronto.ca/people/davison-e-j/|title=Davison E J|website=utoronto.ca|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.control.utoronto.ca/people/profs/ted/bio.html|title=Biography|website=utoronto.ca||accessdate=19 April 2020}}</re