an=\"2\" | [[Golden Joystick Awards]] 2019\n| Still Playing Award\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards|title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards|first=Stephen|last=Tailby|date=September 20, 2019|publisher=Push Square|accessdate=September 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920222955/http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Esports Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[The Game Awards 2019]]\n| Best Ongoing Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/|title=The Game Awards 2019 Nominees Full List|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|date=November 19, 2019|website=GameSpot|accessdate=November 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123042344/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/|archive-date=November 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Community Support\n| {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n===Controversy===\nOn November 2, 2018, Ubisoft Montreal announced they were going to make \"aesthetic changes\" to ''Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege'' by removing references to death, sex, and gambling in order to comply with regulations of Asian countries. However, the announcement generated opposition from the gaming community who believed the changes were going to be made for the game's upcoming release in China, likening the move to [[Video game censorship|censorship]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Parlock |first1=Joe |title='Rainbow Six Siege' In Censorship Row As \"Aesthetic Changes\" Are Made To Fit Asian Regulations |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/11/02/rainbow-six-siege-in-censorship-row-as-aesthetic-changes-are-made-to-fit-asian-regulations/ |magazine=Forbes |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |date=November 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524191344/https://www.forbes.com/sites/joeparlock/2018/11/02/rainbow-six-siege-in-censorship-row-as-aesthetic-changes-are-made-to-fit-asian-regulations/ |archive-date=May 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Because of pressure from the community, Ubisoft Montreal announced on November 21 that they were reversing the decision to make the changes, \"We have been following the conversation with our community closely over the past couple of weeks, alongside regular discussions with our internal Ubisoft team, and we want to ensure that the experience for all our players, especially those that have been with us from the beginning, remains as true to the original artistic intent as possible.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Charlie |title=Rainbow Six Siege team reverses course, will not censor the game for global players |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/21/18106429/rainbow-six-siege-removes-censorship-china |website=Polygon |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |date=November 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517024033/https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/21/18106429/rainbow-six-siege-removes-censorship-china |archive-date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://rainbow6.ubi.com/}}\n\n{{Tom Clancy games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rainbow Six Siege, Tom Clancy's}}\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Asymmetrical multiplayer video games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 5 games]]\n[[Category:Hero shooters]]\n[[Category:Tactical shooter video games]]\n[[Category:Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six]]\n[[Category:Tom Clancy games]]\n[[Category:Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six games]]\n[[Category:Ubisoft games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games set in France]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Germany]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Russia]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Seoul]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Spain]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games using Havok]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox (4th generation) games]]\n[[Category:Video games about terrorism]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 2010s]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Video games containing battle passes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Online tactical shooter video game by Ubisoft}}{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege\n| image = Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege cover art.jpg\n| developer = [[Ubisoft Montreal]]{{efn|Additional work by [[Ubisoft Kiev]], [[Ubisoft Toronto]], [[Ubisoft Barcelona]].}}\n| publisher = [[Ubisoft]]\n| director = Xavier Marquis\n| producer = S\u00e9bastien Labb\u00e9\n| designer = Daniel Drapeau\n| programmer = Jalal Eddine El Mansouri\n| artist = Po Yuen Kenny Lam\n| writer = Li Kuo\n| composer = {{ubl|[[Paul Haslinger]]|[[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]]}}\n| series = ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six]]''\n| engine = [[Anvil (game engine)|AnvilNext 2.0]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[PlayStation 5]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Xbox Series X]]}}\n| released = '''Microsoft Windows''', '''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One'''{{Video game release|WW|December 1, 2015}}'''PlayStation 5''', '''Xbox Series X'''{{Video game release|WW|Q4 2020}}\n| genre = [[Tactical shooter]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n{{Rainbow Six Siege series}}\n\n'''''Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege''''' is an [[Online game|online]] [[tactical shooter]] [[video game]] developed by [[Ubisoft Montreal]] and published by [[Ubisoft]]. It was released worldwide for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]] on December 1, 2015. It was also set to be released for [[PlayStation 5]] and [[Xbox Series X]]. The game puts heavy emphasis on environmental destruction and cooperation between players. Each player assumes control of an attacker or a defender in different gameplay modes such as rescuing a hostage, defusing a bomb, and taking control of an objective within a room. The title has no campaign but features a series of short, offline missions called, \"situations\" that can be played solo. These missions have a loose narrative, focusing on recruits going through training to prepare them for future encounters with the \"White Masks\", a terrorist group that threatens the safety of the world. \n\nIt is an entry in the ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six]]'' series and the successor to ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow 6: Patriots]]'', a tactical shooter that had a larger focus on narrative. However, ''Patriots'' was eventually cancelled due to its technical shortcomings, and the team decided to reboot the franchise. The team evaluated the core of the ''Rainbow Six'' franchise and believed that letting players impersonate the top counter-terrorist operatives around the world suited the game most. To create authentic siege situations, the team consulted actual [[counter-terrorism unit]]s and looked at real-life examples of sieges such as the Iranian Embassy siege. Powered by [[Anvil (game engine)|AnvilNext 2.0]], the game also utilizes Ubisoft's RealBlast technology to create destructible environments.\n\nAnnounced at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2014]], it received four nominations from [[Game Critics Awards]] including Best of Show. The game received an overall positive reception from critics, with praise mostly directed to the game's tense multiplayer and focus on tactics. However, the game was criticized for its progression system and its lack of content. Initial sales were weak, but the game's player base increased significantly as Ubisoft adopted a \"[[games as a service]]\" model for the game and subsequently released several packages of free [[downloadable content]]. Several years after the game's release, some critics regarded ''Siege'' as one of the best multiplayer games in the modern market due to the improvements brought by the post-launch updates. The company partnered with [[ESL (eSports)|ESL]] to make ''Siege'' an [[esports]] game. In February 2019, the game surpassed 45 million registered players across all platforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-player-count|title=Rainbow Six Siege player count tops 40 million|last=Bailey|first=Dustin|date=October 30, 2018|work=PCgamesn|access-date=November 10, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104131428/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-player-count|archive-date=November 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|An alpha gameplay screenshot of the game, showcasing the Hostage Mode. Players can destroy structures like walls to spot targets.]]\n''Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege'' is a [[first-person shooter]] game, in which players utilize many different operators from the Rainbow team. Different operators have different nationalities, weapons, and gadgets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/4/8731885/rainbow-six-siege-fbi-swat-video|title=Meet Rainbow Six Siege's FBI SWAT operators|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=June 4, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101180846/http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/4/8731885/rainbow-six-siege-fbi-swat-video|archive-date=January 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The game features an [[asymmetrical]] structure whereby the teams are not always balanced in their choices of abilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jun/13/e3-2014-rainbow-six-siege-preview|title=E3 2014: Rainbow Six Siege preview|first=Nick|last=Cowen|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=June 13, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630222321/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jun/13/e3-2014-rainbow-six-siege-preview|archive-date=June 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The base Counter-Terrorism Units (CTUs) available for play are the American [[Hostage Rescue Team]] (referred to in-game as the [[FBI Special Weapons and Tactics Teams|FBI SWAT]]), the British [[Special Air Service|SAS]], the German [[GSG 9|GSG-9]], the Russian [[Spetsnaz]] and the French [[GIGN]], each of which has four operators per unit split between attackers and defenders (other units were later added through [[downloadable content]], see [[#Release|below]]). Players also have access to a \"Recruit\" operator who can choose from a more flexible assortment of equipment at the expense of having a unique gadget or the ability to customize their weapon. Players can pick any operator from any unit that is defending or attacking before a round starts, choosing spawn points as well attachments on their guns but are not allowed to change their choices once the round has started. An in-game shop allows players to purchase operators or cosmetics using the in-game currency, \"Renown\", which is earned at the end of matches from actions performed in-game. Different gameplay modes award renown at different rates, with ranked matches offering the largest renown multiplier potential per match. Players can also complete in-game \"challenges\" to get a small amount of renown. Renown gain rate can also be affected by the using in-game \"boosters\" which gives the player a 100% increase in all renown earned for various duration, starting with 24 hours. A premium currency known as \"R6 credits\" can also be purchased using real-world currency to get operators quicker in-game, or other cosmetic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.ubi.com/en-gb/Faqs/000025856/Information-about-Renown-and-R6-credits|title=Information about Renown and R6 credits|access-date=January 11, 2018|website=ubi.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111164932/https://support.ubi.com/en-gb/Faqs/000025856/Information-about-Renown-and-R6-credits|archive-date=January 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen the round begins in an online match, the attackers choose one of several spawn points from which to launch their attack while defenders do the same from which to defend from. A one-minute preparatory period will then commence wherein the attackers are then given control over [[Mecanum wheel|mecanum]]-wheeled [[Unmanned ground vehicle|drones]] to scout the map in search of enemy operators, traps and defensive set-ups in addition to the target objective(s),<ref name=\"VG1\"/> while the opposition establishes their defences and tries to do so without having the defensive and target objective(s) details being discovered, chiefly through destroying the drones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/seven-things-i-wish-id-known-before-starting-rainbow-six-siege/|title=Seven things I wish I\u2019d known before starting Rainbow Six Siege|first=James|last=Davenport|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=May 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529045931/http://www.pcgamer.com/seven-things-i-wish-id-known-before-starting-rainbow-six-siege/|archive-date=May 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Maps in the game are designed to encourage [[close quarters combat]], and players cannot [[spawning (video gaming)|respawn]] until the end of a round. Players who were killed by opponents can enter \"Support Mode\", which allows them to gain access to drone's cameras and security cameras so that they can continue to contribute to their team by informing them of opponent locations and activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/why-there-are-no-respawns-in-the-next-rainbow-six-1646253702|title=Why There Are No Respawns In The Next Rainbow Six|first=Yannick|last=LeJacq|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206210828/https://kotaku.com/why-there-are-no-respawns-in-the-next-rainbow-six-1646253702|archive-date=December 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/why-rainbow-six-siege-doesnt-let-you-respawn/1100-6422962/|title=Why Rainbow Six Siege Doesn't Let You Respawn|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=October 15, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205015747/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/why-rainbow-six-siege-doesnt-let-you-respawn/1100-6422962/|archive-date=December 5, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Matches last only four minutes for a casual and three minutes for a ranked.<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Teamwork and cooperation are encouraged in ''Siege'', and players need to take advantage of their different abilities in order to complete the objective and defeat the enemy team.<ref name=\"VG1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/previews/rainbow-six-siege-alpha-impressions|title=Rainbow Six Siege alpha impressions|first=Steven|last=Burns|work=VideoGamer.com|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704093023/https://www.videogamer.com/previews/rainbow-six-siege-alpha-impressions|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Communication between players is also heavily encouraged.<ref name=\"VG1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology-science/technology/e3-2014-rainbow-six-siege-3683640|title=E3 2014: Rainbow Six: Siege details emerge as Ubisoft unveil explosive hostage situation shooter|first=Rory|last=Buckeridge|work=[[Mirror.co.uk]]|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619233302/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology-science/technology/e3-2014-rainbow-six-siege-3683640|archive-date=June 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The game also has a [[Audience|spectator]] mode, which allows players to observe a match from different angles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/08/14/why-ubisoft-put-spectator-mode-in-rainbow-six-siege/|title=Why Ubisoft put Spectator Mode in Rainbow Six: Siege|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG 247]]|date=August 14, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206013838/https://www.vg247.com/2015/08/14/why-ubisoft-put-spectator-mode-in-rainbow-six-siege/|archive-date=December 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game features a heavy emphasis on environmental destruction<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/ubisoft-talks-single-player-in-rainbow-six-siege-276740.phtml|title=Ubisoft talks single-player in Rainbow Six: Siege|first=Jordan|last=Devore|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=June 17, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622001206/http://www.destructoid.com/ubisoft-talks-single-player-in-rainbow-six-siege-276740.phtml|archive-date=June 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"PCG1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-interview-how-destruction-works-moddability-hostage-design/|title=Rainbow Six Siege interview: how destruction works, moddability, hostage design|first=Evan|last=Lahti|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=June 18, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701024608/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-interview-how-destruction-works-moddability-hostage-design/|archive-date=July 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> using a procedural destruction system. Players can break structures by planting explosives on them, or shoot walls to make bullet holes.<ref name=\"PolyPre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/6/11/5799306/rainbow-six-siege-procedural-destruction|title=Rainbow Six Siege lets you do damage in creative ways|first=Tracey|last=Lien|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627070750/http://www.polygon.com/2014/6/11/5799306/rainbow-six-siege-procedural-destruction|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Players may gain tactical advantages through environmental destruction, and the system aims at encouraging players to utilize creativity and strategy.<ref name=\"PolyPre\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/feature/a643019/hands-on-with-tactical-destruction-filled-shooter-rainbow-six-siege.html#~pgSxtU7aNposjf|title=Hands-on with tactical, destruction-filled shooter Rainbow Six Siege|first=Mark|last=Langshaw|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=April 28, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720050151/http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/feature/a643019/hands-on-with-tactical-destruction-filled-shooter-rainbow-six-siege.html#~pgSxtU7aNposjf|archive-date=July 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A bullet-penetration system is featured, in which bullets that pass through structures deal less damage to enemies.<ref name=\"PCG1\"/> In addition to destruction, players on the defending team can also set up a limited number of heavy-duty fortifications on walls and deployable shields around them for protection; these can be destroyed through breaching devices, explosives, or by utilizing operator specific gadgets in the case of the former.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ubi.com/rainbow-six-siege-destruction-fortification-hostages/|title=Rainbow Six Siege - Destruction, Fortification And Other Modes|first=Anne|last=Lewis|publisher=[[Ubisoft]]|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701003431/http://blog.ubi.com/rainbow-six-siege-destruction-fortification-hostages/|archivedate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> In order to stop attackers' advance, defenders can place traps like [[Barbed_wire|barbed-wire]] and explosive laser wire traps around the maps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/15/8786455/angela-bassett-leads-team-rainbow-rainbow-six-siege|title=Rainbow Six: Siege Closed Alpha Impressions: What Hostage?|first=Steven|last=Wong|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701012209/http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/15/8786455/angela-bassett-leads-team-rainbow-rainbow-six-siege|archive-date=July 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Vertical space is a key gameplay element in the game's maps: players can destroy ceilings and floors using breach charges and can ambush enemies by rappelling through windows.<ref name=\"VG1\"/> Powerful weapons like grenades and breach charges are valuable, as only a limited amount can be used in a round.<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/30/6-things-we-think-about-rainbow-six-siege|title=6 Thing We Think About Rainbow Six Siege|first=Ryan|last=Mccaffrey|work=[[IGN]]|date=March 30, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611122141/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/30/6-things-we-think-about-rainbow-six-siege|archive-date=June 11, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Modes===\nAt launch, the game featured 11 maps<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-will-launch-with-ten-maps/|title=Rainbow Six Siege will launch with 11 multiplayer maps|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|date=September 16, 2015|accessdate=May 31, 2016|work=[[PC Gamer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616135224/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-will-launch-with-ten-maps/|archive-date=June 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and 5 different gameplay modes spanning both [[Player versus environment|PVE]] and [[Player versus player|PVP]]. With the [[downloadable content]] (DLC) released post-launch with an additional four maps from year one and three maps from year two \u2013 there are currently 20 playable maps. The gameplay modes featured include:\n* '''Hostage''': a competitive multiplayer mode, in which the attackers must extract the hostage from the defenders, while the defenders must prevent that from happening either by eliminating all of the attacking team or successfully defending the hostage until the time expires. A secondary manner of winning can occur if the attacking or defending team accidentally damages the hostage, causing the hostage to \"down\"; if the opposing team can prevent the revival of the hostage, and the hostage bleeds-out and dies, they will win the round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/news-post/75570/siege-is-the-next-rainbow-six-game|title=Siege is the Next Rainbow Six Game|first=Kevin|last=Chieng|work=[[GameTrailers]]|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630222140/http://www.gametrailers.com/news-post/75570/siege-is-the-next-rainbow-six-game|archive-date=June 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''Bomb''': a competitive multiplayer mode, in which the attackers are tasked with locating and defusing one of two bombs. The defenders must stop the attackers by killing all of them or destroying the defuser.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.primagames.com/games/rainbow-six-siege/tips/rainbow-six-siege-bomb-mode-preparation-and-action-phase-tips-and-tricks|title=Rainbow Six Siege - Bomb Mode, Preparation and Action Phase Tips and Tricks|first=Bryan|last=Dawson|work=[[Prima Games]]|date=January 4, 2016|accessdate=May 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808232029/https://www.primagames.com/games/rainbow-six-siege/tips/rainbow-six-siege-bomb-mode-preparation-and-action-phase-tips-and-tricks|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> If all attackers are killed after the defuser is planted, the defuser must still be destroyed for a defending victory.\n* '''Secure Area''': a competitive multiplayer mode, in which the defenders must protect a room with a biohazard container, while the attackers must fight their way in and secure it. The match ends when all players from one team are killed or the biohazard container is secured by the attackers when there are no defenders in the room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.primagames.com/games/rainbow-six-siege/tips/rainbow-six-siege-how-win-secure-area-mode|title=Rainbow Six Siege - How to Win in Secure Area Mode|first=Bryan|last=Dawson|work=[[Prima Games]]|date=January 4, 2016|accessdate=May 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808232124/https://www.primagames.com/games/rainbow-six-siege/tips/rainbow-six-siege-how-win-secure-area-mode|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''Tactical Realism:''' a variation of the standard competitive multiplayer modes, added with the release of the ''Operation Skull Rain'' DLC. The game mode features a heavier emphasis on realism and teamwork, removing most of the heads-up display (HUD) elements, the ability to mark opponents, and the ability to see teammates' contours through walls, while also featuring the addition of a realistic ammo management system.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-skull-rain-goes-to-brazil-for-two-new-operators/|title=Rainbow Six Siege: Operation Skull Rain goes to Brazil for two new operators|work=PC Gamer|access-date=December 5, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206074550/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-skull-rain-goes-to-brazil-for-two-new-operators/|archive-date=December 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> This mode is no longer in the game but some aspects are in the other multiplayer modes.\n* '''Terrorist Hunt''': a solo<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/09/29/no-rainbow-six-siege-story-campaign-try-lone-wolfing-terrorist-hunt/|title=No Rainbow Six: Siege story campaign? Try lone wolfing Terrorist Hunt|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=September 30, 2015|work=[[VG247]]|first=Matt|last=Martin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930210231/http://www.vg247.com/2015/09/29/no-rainbow-six-siege-story-campaign-try-lone-wolfing-terrorist-hunt/|archive-date=September 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> or [[cooperative gameplay|cooperative multiplayer mode]] for up to five players. Players take on the role of either attackers or defenders, and must fight against waves of enemies controlled by [[artificial intelligence]] across various modes like Bomb, Hostage or Elimination (Terrorist hunt classic).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-06-15-rainbow-six-siege-player-vs-ai-terrohunt-mode-detailed|title=Rainbow Six Siege player-vs-AI Terrohunt mode detailed|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=June 16, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630200107/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-06-15-rainbow-six-siege-player-vs-ai-terrohunt-mode-detailed|archive-date=June 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GSpot tense\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-crushing-tension-of-rainbow-six-siege-at-e3-20/1100-6428133/|title=The Crushing Tension of Rainbow Six: Siege at E3 2015|first=Kevin|last=VanOrd|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619033355/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-crushing-tension-of-rainbow-six-siege-at-e3-20/1100-6428133/|archive-date=June 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''Situations''': the game's most significant single-player component, with 10 solo and 1 co-op multiplayer missions that serve as introductory and interactive tutorials to the game's mechanics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/21/introducing-rainbow-six-sieges-single-player-mode|title=Introducing Rainbow Six Siege's Single-player Mode|first=Alex|last=Simmons|work=[[IGN]]|date=October 21, 2015|accessdate=May 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527150017/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/21/introducing-rainbow-six-sieges-single-player-mode|archive-date=May 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''Outbreak:''' A limited time event exclusive to Operation Chimera, Outbreak pits a 3 player team in a co-op PVE environment against an [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] biohazard threat, namely AI-controlled heavily mutated forms of humans infected with said alien parasite. Two difficulties exists for this mode, for which the chief difference was the inclusion of friendly fire on the harder one.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.windowscentral.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-chimera|title=Rainbow Six Siege Operation Chimera: Everything you need to know|work=Windows Central|access-date=June 8, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141450/https://www.windowscentral.com/rainbow-six-siege-operation-chimera|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Setting==\n[[File:Angela Bassett by Gage Skidmoe.jpg|thumb|140px|right|[[Angela Bassett]] performed voice works and motion capture for Six, the director of Team Rainbow.]]\nThree years after the Rainbow Program's deactivation, there is a resurgence of terrorist activities, with the White Mask being the most prominent. The terrorists' goals are unknown, yet they are causing chaos across the world.<ref name=\"story and setting\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.ubi.com/rainbow-six-siege-single-player-terrohunt-modes/|title=Rainbow Six Siege - Single-player And TerroHunt|first=Anne|last=Lewis|publisher=[[Ubisoft]]|date=January 15, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701003428/http://blog.ubi.com/rainbow-six-siege-single-player-terrohunt-modes/|archivedate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> To counter this rising threat, the program is reactivated by a new leader who is simply known as Six (voiced by [[Angela Bassett]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/06/15/rainbow-six-siege-e3-2015/|title='Rainbow Six Siege' has Angela Bassett, beta launches September 24th|first=Richard|last=Lawler|work=[[Engadget]]|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619020154/http://www.engadget.com/2015/06/15/rainbow-six-siege-e3-2015/|archive-date=June 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Six assembles a group of special forces operatives from different countries to face and combat the White Masks. Recruits go through multiple exercises to prepare them for future encounters with the White Masks, training to perform hostage rescue and bomb disposal. Eventually, the White Masks launch a chemical attack on a university (called Bartlett University), and the recruits are sent to disarm the bombs and eliminate the enemy presence. The operation is a massive success, though there are casualties. The story ends with Six affirming that the reactivation of Team Rainbow is the best and only choice in a time filled with risks and uncertainties. Team Rainbow is ready for their next mission \u2013 to hunt down the leader of their enemy \u2013 and they stand prepared to protect and defend their nation from terrorists.\n\n==Development==\n{{see also|Tom Clancy's Rainbow 6: Patriots}}\n{{quote|quote=This entire project was born and has grown out of an in-depth study that looked to distill what the ''Rainbow'' series is at its core in terms of both fantasy and gameplay. At the end of the day, the ''Rainbow Six'' fantasy about being part of the greatest counter-terrorist organization and impersonating the best of the best operators, working as a team, [and] carrying out dangerous operations (hostage rescue) anywhere on the globe|source=Andrew J. Witts, game designer of ''Rainbow Six: Siege''<ref name=\"lean\"/>}}\nThe game's predecessor was ''Tom Clancy's Rainbow 6: Patriots'', a [[tactical shooter]] announced in 2011. It had a focus on narrative, and the story campaign features many cut-scenes and scripted events. However, the game fell into a [[development hell]] shortly after its announcement. The game's outdated engine and frequent change of <!--production -->leadership hindered development progress, and game quality was not up to par.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/06/17/rainbow-six-patriots-canceled/|title=Why Rainbow Six Patriots Got Canceled In Favor Of Siege|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=June 17, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802124306/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/06/17/rainbow-six-patriots-canceled/|archive-date=August 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, it was planned to be released on [[seventh generation of video game consoles|seventh-generation video-game consoles]] which were not capable of processing certain game mechanics. Seeing the arrival of a new generation of consoles, the team wanted to make use of this opportunity to create a more technologically advanced game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2014/6/9/5792660/rainbow-six-patriots-canceled-replaced-by-rainbow-six-siege|title=Rainbow 6: Patriots canceled, replaced by Rainbow Six Siege|first=Brian|last=Crecente|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802122837/https://www.polygon.com/2014/6/9/5792660/rainbow-six-patriots-canceled-replaced-by-rainbow-six-siege|archive-date=August 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, Ubisoft decided to cancel ''Patriots'' and assembled a new team of 25 people to come up with ideas to [[reboot (fiction)|reboot]] the series.<ref name=\"reboot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2017/02/14/rainbow-six-siege-interview-future/|title=The origins & future of Rainbow Six Siege|first=Jake|last=Tucker|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=February 14, 2017|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802163549/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2017/02/14/rainbow-six-siege-interview-future/|archive-date=August 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTo make the new game feel refreshing, only certain multiplayer elements were retained as the small team took the game in a different direction. They evaluated the core of the ''[[Rainbow Six]]'' series, which they thought was about being a member of a counter-terrorist team travelling around the globe to deal with dangerous terrorist attacks \u2013 operations which are usually intense confrontations between attackers and defenders.<ref name=\"lean\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/01/23/rainbow-six-siege-5v5-or-bust-ign-first|title=Rainbow Six Siege: 5v5 On Bust - IGN First|first=Ryan|last=McCaffery|work=[[IGN]]|date=June 14, 2017|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802124308/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/01/23/rainbow-six-siege-5v5-or-bust-ign-first|archive-date=August 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the team wanted to fit these ideas into a multiplayer format which would increase the game's sustainability.<ref name=\"unbreakable\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-dev-canceled-patriots-to-focus-o/1100-6442272/?ftag=GSS-05-10aaa0b|title=Rainbow Six Siege Dev Canceled Patriots to Focus on Competitive Multiplayer|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=August 1, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809132426/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-dev-canceled-patriots-to-focus-o/1100-6442272/?ftag=GSS-05-10aaa0b|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/19/the-strange-life-and-death-of-rainbow-6-patriots-2|title=The Strange Life And Death of Rainbow Six Patriots|first=Mitch|last=Dyer|work=[[IGN]]|date=June 19, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809131736/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/19/the-strange-life-and-death-of-rainbow-6-patriots-2|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> These became the basic concept ideas for the game. As the development team hoped that the game can be replayed frequently, the team decided to devote all the resources into developing the game's multiplayer and abandoned the single-player campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/02/10/ubisoft-talks-rainbow-six-siege-netcode-clan-support-and-most-popular-operators.aspx?|title=Ubisoft Talks Rainbow Six Siege Netcode, Clan Support, And Most Popular Operators|first=Matt|last=Bertz|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=February 10, 2016|accessdate=June 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809130647/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/02/10/ubisoft-talks-rainbow-six-siege-netcode-clan-support-and-most-popular-operators.aspx|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of the game officially began in January 2013. [[Ubisoft Montreal]], the developer of ''Patriots'', handled the game's development, with Ubisoft's offices in [[Ubisoft Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Ubisoft Toronto|Toronto]], [[Ubisoft Kiev|Kiev]], [[Ubisoft Shanghai|Shanghai]] and [[Ubisoft Chengdu|Chengdu]] providing assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static9.cdn.ubisoft.com/ubigroupstatic/en-US/global/img/company/Studio_profiles_September_2016_English_268341.pdf|title=Creativity At The Core|publisher=[[Ubisoft]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809131353/http://static9.cdn.ubisoft.com/ubigroupstatic/en-US/global/img/company/Studio_profiles_September_2016_English_268341.pdf|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/18/rainbow-six-patriots-shot-dead-as-it-was-old-gen|title=Rainbow Six Patriots Shot Dead As It Was 'Old Gen'|first=Luke|last=Karmali|work=[[IGN]]|date=June 18, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809133642/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/18/rainbow-six-patriots-shot-dead-as-it-was-old-gen|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was originally called ''Rainbow Six Unbreakable'', a title that reflected not only the game's destruction mechanic but also the mindset of the development team, who had to deliver a game that was once stuck in development hell.<ref name=\"unbreakable\"/> According to Alexandre Remy, the brand director, the team was confident in their new vision for the game but very nervous when they revealed it, realizing the change of direction would likely disappoint some fans.<ref name=\"reboot\"/>\n\n===Design===\nThe 150-person team consisted mainly of [[first-person shooter]] veterans or longtime ''Rainbow Six'' players.<ref name=\"unbreakable\"/> Despite having prior knowledge on how these types of games work, the team decided to study historic examples of counter-terrorist operations, including 1980's London [[Iranian Embassy siege]], 1977's [[Lufthansa Flight 181]] hijacking, and 2002's [[Moscow theater hostage crisis|Moscow theatre hostage crisis]] to ensure that the portrayal of these operations was accurate and appropriate. The team also consulted [[counter-terrorism unit]]s, such as the [[National Gendarmerie Intervention Group]] (GIGN), for their opinions on how they would react during a hostage rescue situation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2014/10/21/7033719/how-rainbow-six-siege-takes-inspiration-from-real-life-hostage-rescues|title=How Rainbow Six: Siege takes inspiration from real life hostage rescues|first=Colin|last=Campbell|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=October 21, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209100008/https://www.polygon.com/2014/10/21/7033719/how-rainbow-six-siege-takes-inspiration-from-real-life-hostage-rescues|archive-date=December 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Xavier Marquis, the game's creative director, having a hostage rescue mission in the game helped create an immersive story. By allowing players to assume control of an operator tasked with saving innocents, it gives them an objective and a priority. They must be careful in dealing with the situation and try their best not to hurt the hostage. This further promotes teamwork between players and prompts them to plan before attacking, and further makes the game more realistic, tense and immersive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/10/21/how-real-life-events-influenced-rainbow-six-siege|title=How Real-Life Events Influenced Rainbow Six Siege|first=Cassidee|last=Moser|work=[[IGN]]|date=October 21, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607044652/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/10/21/how-real-life-events-influenced-rainbow-six-siege|archive-date=June 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> To make the game feel more realistic, the team introduced a mechanic called \"living hostage\" to govern the hostage character's behaviour \u2013 e.g., coughing if there is dust in the air or shielding him or herself if there is nearby gunfire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/06/26/rainbow-six-siege-to-include-male-hostages-too/|title=Rainbow Six: Siege to include male hostages, too|first=Jessica|last=Conditt|work=[[Engadget]]|date=June 26, 2014|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209044110/https://www.engadget.com/2014/06/26/rainbow-six-siege-to-include-male-hostages-too/|archive-date=December 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe environmental destruction mechanic was one of the game's most important elements. When the game's development was begun, the developer's in-house team completed their work on RealBlast Destruction, an engine that \"procedurally breaks everything down\" and remodels the environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ubi.com/the-art-of-destruction-in-rainbow-six-siege-an-interview-with-julien-lheureux/|title=The Art of Destruction In Rainbow Six - An Interview With Julien L'Heureux|publisher=[[Ubisoft]]|work=UbiBlog|date=March 11, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809131938/http://blog.ubi.com/the-art-of-destruction-in-rainbow-six-siege-an-interview-with-julien-lheureux/|archivedate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> The development team thought that this technology fitted the game's style and gameplay, and decided to use it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/rainbow-six-siege-interview-finding-meaning-in-destruction|title=Rainbow Six Siege Interview: Finding Meaning in Destruction|first=Mike|last=Williams|work=[[USgamer]]|date=October 7, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510071131/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/rainbow-six-siege-interview-finding-meaning-in-destruction|archive-date=May 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> This aspect of the game became increasingly important during development, and the team spent an extended period of time making sure that these destructions were authentic. As a result, the team implemented a materials-based tearing system, in which environmental objects of different materials show different reactions to players' attacks.<ref name=\"PCG1\"/> To render the game's texture, the team used [[physically based rendering]], even though it was ineffective during the game's early stage of production due to issues with the game's engine. A material bank and substance painter were utilized to create textures for environmental objects when they were damaged or destroyed. The team also implemented subtle visual cues to help players identify whether a structure was destructible or not, as opposed to \"distracting\" players with more-obvious hints.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.develop-online.net/interview/breaking-down-the-right-walls-ubisoft-montreal-on-texturing-rainbow-six-siege-s-destructible-world/0219230|title=Breaking down the (right) walls: Ubisoft Montreal on texturing Rainbow Six Siege's destructible world|first=Matthew|last=Jarvis|work=[[Develop (magazine)|Develop]]|date=April 15, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810083236/http://www.develop-online.net/interview/breaking-down-the-right-walls-ubisoft-montreal-on-texturing-rainbow-six-siege-s-destructible-world/0219230|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The destruction mechanic prompted Ubisoft to change their level-design approach, as they had to ensure that the level was still logical and realistic when parts of the environment were destroyed.<ref name=\"postmortem\">{{cite web|url=http://www.develop-online.net/analysis/the-develop-post-mortem-rainbow-six-siege/0233146|title=The Develop Post-Mortem: Rainbow Six Siege|work=[[Develop (magazine)|Develop]]|date=May 31, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605062500/http://www.develop-online.net/analysis/the-develop-post-mortem-rainbow-six-siege/0233146|archive-date=June 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ubisoft, \"teamwork, tactics, and tension\" were the game's three most important pillars. The team initially worked on a respawn feature, allowing players to rejoin after they are killed in the game. However, following several internal tournaments, the team realized that some of their employees would always win a match. They concluded that the respawn system worked to the benefit of strong players and placed individual skill above teamwork,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/ubisoft-explains-why-you-wont-respawn-in-rainbow-six-siege/|title=Ubisoft explains why you won't respawn in Rainbow Six Siege|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=October 14, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809170956/http://www.pcgamer.com/ubisoft-explains-why-you-wont-respawn-in-rainbow-six-siege/|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> which did not fit the developer's focus on game tactics. Removing the respawn feature meant greater consequences for taking risks, and players had to rely on their teammates in order to survive and achieve objectives. According to Chris Lee, the game's designer, the team initially worried that the system would only appeal to hardcore players. However, after several testings, they found that the removal of the respawn system provided new challenges to strong players and forced them to cooperate with their teammates \u2013 while it rewarded weaker players who were willing to take their time, plan their actions, and be strategic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/why-rainbow-six-siege-doesnt-let-you-respawn/1100-6422962/|title=Why Rainbow Six Siege Doesn't Let You Respawn|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=October 14, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809131650/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/why-rainbow-six-siege-doesnt-let-you-respawn/1100-6422962/|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"FP\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/inside-rainbow-six-sieges-development|title=Inside Rainbow Six: Siege's Development|first=Jaz|last=Rignall|work=[[USgamer]]|date=November 22, 2015|accessdate=June 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809170953/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/inside-rainbow-six-sieges-development|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay system was designed to allow players to have a lot of freedom. As a result, the team implemented the \"Golden 3C Rules\", which represents Character, Control, and Camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-video-promises-complete-player-control/|title=Rainbow Six Siege video promises complete player control|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=December 5, 2014|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218125902/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-video-promises-complete-player-control/|archive-date=December 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Players are always controlling their own actions and movements, and the team intentionally avoided any animation that would disrupt the players. As a result, actions such as setting explosives, or placing a breach charge, can be cancelled immediately so that players can react and shoot. The game's camera only moves when the player moves, as the team feared that the changes of camera angle may lead to players' in-game deaths. A free-lean system was introduced to the game so that players can have more control over their line of sight.<ref name=\"lean\"/> According to Ubisoft, this input-driven control mechanism makes the game feel more \"natural\" and \"fluid\". This is because it allows players to concentrate on planning and coordinating, rather than thinking if the camera or environment will interfere with their actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rainbow6.ubisoft.com/siege/en-us/news/detail.aspx?c=tcm:152-187149-16&ct=tcm:148-76770-32|title=Behind The Wall: Cover and Lean|first=Chase|last=Straight|work=UbiBlog|publisher=[[Ubisoft]]|date=December 2, 2014|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSeveral gameplay elements were scrapped or removed from the final game. One of the features of its predecessors, [[artificial intelligence]]-controlled squadmates, were removed from single-player missions. This decision was made because the team wanted players to play with a squad controlled by actual players rather than computers. The team once considered adding a map editor so that players could design their own maps, but this plan never came to fruition. Hit markers, which would indicate an injury inflicted on an opponent, were removed because the team feared that players would abuse the system by \"peppering the walls with gunfire\" and use hit markers to locate enemies. Players cannot jump in the game, as real-life counter-terrorist unit operators do not jump while carrying out their missions.<ref name=\"FP\">{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/developer-interview-we-ask-what-rainbow-six-siege-brings-to-the-table-after-eight-years-away|title=Developer interview: We ask what Rainbow Six Siege brings to the table after eight years away|first=Chad|last=Sapihea|work=Post Arcade|publisher=[[Financial Post]]|date=November 25, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228073013/https://business.financialpost.com/technology/gaming/developer-interview-we-ask-what-rainbow-six-siege-brings-to-the-table-after-eight-years-away|archive-date=February 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Louis Philippe, the game's audio director, the team originally used intense music and sounds to create tension. However, the team decided to scrap this idea, realizing that the best way to create a tense atmosphere is to create the sounds of other players, which are often unexpected. The team created Navigation Sounds, in which the sound a player made is determined by their operators' weight, armour, and speed. Gadget deployment such as fortifying and breach-charging create louder sounds that may reveal the player's presence. The team thought that this would be enjoyable for players and influence their gameplay experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/288565/Game_Design_Deep_Dive_Dynamic_audio_in_destructible_levels_in_Rainbow_Six_Siege.php|title=Game Design Deep Dive: Dynamic audio in destructible levels in Rainbow Six: Siege|first=Louis|last=Philippe Dion|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=January 18, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613040057/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/288565/Game_Design_Deep_Dive_Dynamic_audio_in_destructible_levels_in_Rainbow_Six_Siege.php|archive-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The game's music was composed by [[Paul Haslinger]], who had worked on the score of the previous ''Rainbow Six'' games and the ''[[Far Cry]]'' series. His co-composer was [[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]], who debuted his first video game soundtrack with ''Siege''. Leon Purviance assisted Frost and Haslinger in composing the music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vgmonline.net/rainbow-six-siege-composers-and-soundtrack-detailed/|title=Rainbow Six: Siege composers and soundtrack detailed|first=Chris|last=Grenning|work=VGMOnline|date=November 27, 2015|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621115210/http://www.vgmonline.net/rainbow-six-siege-composers-and-soundtrack-detailed/|archive-date=June 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nUbisoft announced the game at their press conference during [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/09/e3-2014-rainbow-six-siege-revealed|title=E3 2014: Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege Revealed|first=Brian|last=Albert|work=[[IGN]]|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811225421/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/09/e3-2014-rainbow-six-siege-revealed|archive-date=August 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2015, Ubisoft announced that they had delayed the game's release from October 10 to December 1, 2015, in order to give additional time for the team to balance the game for cooperative multiplayer play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-08-18-rainbow-six-siege-delayed-to-december|title=Rainbow Six Siege delayed to December|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=August 18, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811223238/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-08-18-rainbow-six-siege-delayed-to-december|archive-date=August 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A closed alpha-testing was held by Ubisoft on April 7\u201313, 2015, in which players could play an early version of the game in order to help the development team test their servers and core gameplay loops, and to provide feedback.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-pc-closed-alpha-starts-next-week/1100-6426404/|title=Rainbow Six Siege PC Closed Alpha Starts Next Week|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209044152/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-pc-closed-alpha-starts-next-week/1100-6426404/|archive-date=December 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Ubisoft held a closed beta, starting on September 24, 2015, for further testing. The company originally wanted to hold another round of testing with the release of the game's open beta on November 25, 2015, but they delayed its release to November 26 due to [[Matchmaking (video games)|matchmaking]] issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-11-25-rainbow-six-siege-open-beta-delayed|title=Rainbow Six: Siege open beta delayed|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811223335/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-11-25-rainbow-six-siege-open-beta-delayed|archive-date=August 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Players who purchased ''Siege'' for the Xbox One could download ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six: Vegas]]'' and its sequel, ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six: Vegas 2]]'' for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/06/15/e3-2015-rainbow-six-vegas-1-and-2-free-with-siege-on-xbox-one|title=E3 2015: Rainbow Six Vegas 1 and 2 Free With Siege on Xbox One|first=Marty|last=Silva|work=[[IGN]]|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618092948/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/06/15/e3-2015-rainbow-six-vegas-1-and-2-free-with-siege-on-xbox-one|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> To launch the game in Asian markets, Ubisoft announced plans to remove graphic imagery from all versions of the game via a patch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/2018/11/03/ubisoft-removing-graphic-imagery-from-rainbow-six-siege-as-it-expands-to-asian-market|title=Ubisoft Removing Graphic Imagery From Rainbow Six Siege As It Expands To Asian Market|first=Suriel|last=Vazquez|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=November 3, 2018|accessdate=November 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104125910/https://www.gameinformer.com/2018/11/03/ubisoft-removing-graphic-imagery-from-rainbow-six-siege-as-it-expands-to-asian-market|archive-date=November 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The plan was later withdrawn by the developer due to [[review bomb]]ing and negative fans feedback.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-11-21-on-ubisofts-pandering-to-unreasonable-players|title=On Ubisoft's pandering to unreasonable players|first=James|last=Batchelor|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=November 21, 2018|accessdate=November 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128164640/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-11-21-on-ubisofts-pandering-to-unreasonable-players|archive-date=November 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game had multiple versions for players to purchase. A [[Season pass (video gaming)|season pass]] was announced on November 12, 2015. Players who bought this version of the game could gain early access to operators offered in the [[downloadable content|DLCs]] and receive several weapon skins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/heres-everything-the-rainbow-six-siege-dlc-season-/1100-6432231/|title=Here's Everything the Rainbow Six Siege DLC Season Pass Gets You|first=Chris|last=Pereira|date=November 12, 2015|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=[[GameSpot]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113190608/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/heres-everything-the-rainbow-six-siege-dlc-season-/1100-6432231/|archive-date=November 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was also released alongside its Collector's Edition, which included the game's season pass, a hat, a compass and bottle opener, a backpack, and a 120-page guide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-collector-s-edition-offers-a-bac/1100-6428401/|title=Rainbow Six: Siege Collector's Edition Offers a Backpack, DLC, and More|first=Chris|last=Pereira|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209044128/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-siege-collector-s-edition-offers-a-bac/1100-6428401/|archive-date=December 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A ''Starter Edition'' was released on PC in June 2016, featuring all content offered in the Standard Edition, and included two operators at start for use plus enough Rainbow 6 Credits to purchase up to two more of the player's choice while the rest has to be purchased through either Renown at an increased cost or additional Rainbow 6 Credits. The Starter Edition was cheaper than the Standard Edition and was initially available for a limited time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-starter-edition-is-now-available-for-15/?|title=Rainbow Six Siege Starter Edition is now available for $15|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 3, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605014005/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-starter-edition-is-now-available-for-15/|archive-date=June 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2017, the Starter Edition became permanently available via [[Uplay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/169511-Rainbow-Six-Siege-Starter-Edition-Returns-to-PC-Permanently#&gid=gallery_6919&pid=1|title=The $15 Rainbow Six Siege Starter Edition is Back on PC|first=Ron|last=Whitaker|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|date=February 10, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209100057/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/169511-Rainbow-Six-Siege-Starter-Edition-Returns-to-PC-Permanently#&gid=gallery_6919&pid=1|archive-date=December 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ubisoft, the game adopted a \"[[games as a service]]\" approach, as they would provide long-term support for the game and offer post-release content to keep players engaged. The management team initially doubted the idea but eventually decided to approve it.<ref name=\"reboot\"/> The title was supported with many updates upon launch, with the company introducing fixes to [[Software bug|bugs]] and improvements on both matchmaking and general gameplay mechanics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-mid-season-reinforcements-update-buffs-glazs-scope/|title=Rainbow Six Siege mid season Reinforcements update buffs Glaz's scope|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=March 14, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627202749/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-mid-season-reinforcements-update-buffs-glazs-scope/|archive-date=June 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-update-ushers-in-a-bunch-of-requested-fixes/|title=Rainbow Six Siege update ushers in a bunch of requested fixes|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=January 10, 2017|accessdate=January 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170114113429/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-update-ushers-in-a-bunch-of-requested-fixes/|archive-date=January 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> To enable players' involvement in the game's continued development, Ubisoft introduced the R6Fix programme in 2018. It allows players to submit bug reports to Ubisoft, which would fix the bug and award the player in-game items.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/341494/Ubisoft_is_rewarding_players_for_reporting_reproducible_bugs_in_Rainbow_Six_Siege.php|title=Ubisoft is rewarding players for reporting reproducible bugs in Rainbow Six Siege|first=Alissa|last=McAloon|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=April 25, 2019|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183432/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/341494/Ubisoft_is_rewarding_players_for_reporting_reproducible_bugs_in_Rainbow_Six_Siege.php|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> They also introduced an auto-kick system, which automatically removes players from a match when they kill friendly players<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/12/16/ubisoft-releases-an-auto-kicker-targeting-rainbow-six-siege-team-killers|title=Ubisoft Release An Auto-Kicker Targeting Rainbow Six Siege Team Killers|first=Matt|last=Potter|work=[[IGN]]|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503091023/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/12/16/ubisoft-releases-an-auto-kicker-targeting-rainbow-six-siege-team-killers|archive-date=May 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and launched the BattleEye system in August 2016 to punish cheaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-new-anti-cheating-tech-already-/1100-6442744/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's New Anti-Cheating Tech Already Going Strong, Has Banned Thousands|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=August 11, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807235424/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-new-anti-cheating-tech-already-/1100-6442744/|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> To counter toxicity within the game's community, in mid 2018 Ubisoft began issuing [[Ban (law)|ban]]s to any player who has used racist and homophobic slurs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-07-14-rainbow-six-siege-now-insta-banning-players-for-using-slurs|title=Rainbow Six Siege instantly bans players for using slurs|first=Rebekah|last=Valentine|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=July 14, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801190421/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-07-14-rainbow-six-siege-now-insta-banning-players-for-using-slurs|archive-date=August 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> All [[downloadable content]] maps were released to all players for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-09-17-all-rainbow-six-siege-dlc-maps-will-be-free-ubisoft-confirms|title=All Rainbow Six Siege DLC maps will be free, Ubisoft confirms|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=September 17, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807235306/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-09-17-all-rainbow-six-siege-dlc-maps-will-be-free-ubisoft-confirms|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> All downloadable operators can be unlocked using the in-game currency though purchasing the season pass enables players to gain instant access to them.<ref name=\"reboot\"/> Players can purchase cosmetic items using real-world money, but the team did not wish to put gameplay content behind a paywall in order to be more player-friendly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-outbreak-packs|title=Rainbow Six Siege microtransactions \"will never affect gameplay\"|first=Ali|last=Jones|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=February 20, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426185643/https://www.pcgamesn.com/rainbow-six-siege/rainbow-six-siege-outbreak-packs|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GI Post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/12/08/how-rainbow-six-siege-quietly-became-one-of-the-best-multiplayer-shooters-.aspx|title=How Rainbow Six Siege Quietly Became One Of The Best Multiplayer Shooters|first=Cody|last=Mello-Klein|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=December 8, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183438/https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/12/08/how-rainbow-six-siege-quietly-became-one-of-the-best-multiplayer-shooters-.aspx|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The team avoided adding more modes to the game because most would not fit well with the game's close-quarter combat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/why-rainbow-six-siege-wont-have-new-game-modes-aims-for-50-100-operators-instead/|title=Why Rainbow Six Siege won't have new game modes, aims for '50-100 operators' instead|first=Stephen|last=Messener|date=February 5, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017|work=[[PC Gamer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613034042/http://www.pcgamer.com/why-rainbow-six-siege-wont-have-new-game-modes-aims-for-50-100-operators-instead/|archive-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Downloadable content for the game was divided into several seasons, with a Mid-Season Reinforcement patch which added new weapons and modified some of the operators' core abilities.<ref name=\"reboot\"/> This post-release content was developed by the Montreal studio in conjunction with [[Ubisoft Blue Byte|Blue Byte]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/for-honor-will-be-on-show-at-the-pc-gamer-weekender/|title=For Honor will be on show at the PC Gamer Weekender|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=January 16, 2016|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807234854/http://www.pcgamer.com/for-honor-will-be-on-show-at-the-pc-gamer-weekender/|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Ubisoft announced that they would keep supporting the game and adding new playable characters for 10 more years. As a result, no sequel was planned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/02/19/rainbow-six-siege-100-operators-10-years-no-sequel/|title=The future of Rainbow Six Siege: 100 operators over 10 years, no sequel|first=Matt|last=Martin|work=[[VG 247]]|date=February 19, 2018|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413191103/https://www.vg247.com/2018/02/19/rainbow-six-siege-100-operators-10-years-no-sequel/|archive-date=April 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Ubisoft announced the introduction of 'Outbreak Packs', which are [[loot box]]es that can be unlocked with R6 credits (which can be purchased with [[microtransaction]]s) to gain character items. The company also announced that the base version of the game will be replaced by a bundle named ''The Advanced Edition'', which includes the base game and a small number of outbreak packs and R6 credits. The changes resulted in players' backlash, as existing players have to pay for new content while new players do not.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2018/01/26/ubisoft-responds-to-rainbow-six-siege-veterans-lootbox-concerns.aspx|title=Ubisoft Responds To Rainbow Six: Siege Veterans' Lootbox Concerns|first=Imran|last=Khan|date=January 26, 2018|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414011825/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2018/01/26/ubisoft-responds-to-rainbow-six-siege-veterans-lootbox-concerns.aspx|archive-date=April 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Ubisoft compensated players by giving players a free premium skin for free and announced plans to change the Standard Edition so that players can unlock new operators at a faster pace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-01-26-rainbow-six-siege-players-unhappy-at-timed-event-with-paid-only-cosmetic-packs|title=Rainbow Six Siege players unhappy at timed-event with paid-only cosmetic packs|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=January 30, 2018|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190154/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-01-26-rainbow-six-siege-players-unhappy-at-timed-event-with-paid-only-cosmetic-packs|archive-date=April 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2018, Ubisoft announced the introduction of a limited time pack named 'Sunsplash Packs', which are available to purchase with R6 credits and contain cosmetics that have an association with the season of Summer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sunsplash Collection is Available Now for a Limited-Time |url=https://rainbow6.ubisoft.com/siege/en-gb/news/detail.aspx?c=tcm:154-330347-16&ct=tcm:154-76770-32 |publisher=Ubisoft |accessdate=July 9, 2018 |language=English |date=July 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709190041/https://rainbow6.ubisoft.com/siege/en-gb/news/detail.aspx?c=tcm:154-330347-16&ct=tcm:154-76770-32 |archive-date=July 9, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2018, Ubisoft unveiled the Crimsonveil packs, which added a Halloween themed weapon skin, charm, headgear, and uniform for 4 operators, plus a seasonal weapon skin and a charm that was themed with the skin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rainbow6.ubisoft.com/siege/en-us/news/152-337187-16/its-a-mad-house|title=It\u2019s a Mad House!|website=rainbow6.ubisoft.com|access-date=November 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126221514/https://rainbow6.ubisoft.com/siege/en-us/news/152-337187-16/its-a-mad-house|archive-date=November 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Esports ===\nUbisoft also envisioned the game as an [[esports]] game. The company had their first meeting with David Hiltscher, vice president of [[ESL (eSports)|ESL]], in late 2013. ESL offered feedback on the game's balancing and helped the developer to ensure that the game was suitable for competitive play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/int-en/making-rainbow-six-siege-into-an-esport-interview|title=Building Rainbow Six Siege into an eSport|first=Steffie|last=Wunderl|work=[[Red Bull GmbH|Red Bull]]|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809131752/https://www.redbull.com/int-en/making-rainbow-six-siege-into-an-esport-interview|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The team focused on introducing new operators to provide variety for esports viewers after the game's release, a decision inspired by modern [[multiplayer online battle arena]] games such as ''[[Dota 2]]'', as this type of game often has 80\u2013100 playable characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/02/06/rainbow-six-siege-is-all-about-new-operators-and-maps-not-new-game-modes/|title=Rainbow Six Siege is all about new operators and maps, not new game modes|first=Shabana|last=Arif|work=[[VG 247]]|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508230826/http://www.vg247.com/2017/02/06/rainbow-six-siege-is-all-about-new-operators-and-maps-not-new-game-modes/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ESL and Ubisoft officially announced Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Pro League, a global tournament for Windows and Xbox One players. The competition was held at Intel Extreme Masters eSports tournament on March 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/news/a781754/rainbow-six-siege-gets-a-100000-tournament/|title=Rainbow Six Siege gets a $100,000 tournament|first=Ian|last=Dransfield|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=January 29, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608192805/http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/news/a781754/rainbow-six-siege-gets-a-100000-tournament/|archive-date=June 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A European team, PENTA Sports, became the champion of the first season of Rainbow Six Pro League after defeating another team, GiFu, at the final of the tournament held in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/what-does-rainbow-6-siege-need-to-make-it-as-an-esport/|title=What does Rainbow 6: Siege need to make it as an esport?|first=Chris|last=Higgins|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=May 19, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809171439/http://www.pcgamer.com/what-does-rainbow-6-siege-need-to-make-it-as-an-esport/|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, it was revealed that Pro League Year Two would return, but Xbox One tournaments would not be featured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-pro-league-year-two-goes-pc-exclusive/|title=Rainbow Six Pro League Year Two goes PC exclusive|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=March 16, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531172214/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-pro-league-year-two-goes-pc-exclusive/|archive-date=May 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Ubisoft also held the Six Invitational tournaments in 2017 and 2018, in which top teams competed for the top prize. The 2018 tournament attracted 321,000 viewers on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/my-after-action-report-of-the-rainbow-six-invitational-tournament-491744.phtml|title=My after-action report of the Rainbow Six Invitational tournament|first=Chris|last=Moyse|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=February 27, 2018|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328010214/https://www.destructoid.com/my-after-action-report-of-the-rainbow-six-invitational-tournament-491744.phtml|archive-date=March 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Both Nathan Lawrence from [[Red Bull GmbH|Red Bull]] and Richie Shoemaker from [[Eurogamer]] compared the game favourably with ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]'', with both being hopeful that ''Siege'' can dethrone ''Global Offensive'''s status as the most successful competitive esports first-person shooter in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/rainbow-six-siege-counter-strike-killer|title=Rainbow Six Siege: Counter-Strike Killer|first=Nathan|last=Lawrence|work=[[Red Bull GmbH|Red Bull]]|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190129/https://www.redbull.com/au-en/rainbow-six-siege-counter-strike-killer|archive-date=April 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-06-a-new-season-of-siege-means-that-rainbow-six-is-a-step-closer-to-taking-down-counter-strike|title=A new season of Siege means that Rainbow Six is a step closer to taking down Counter-Strike|first=Richie|last=Shoemaker|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=September 6, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413185845/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-06-a-new-season-of-siege-means-that-rainbow-six-is-a-step-closer-to-taking-down-counter-strike|archive-date=April 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Rainbow Six Siege Year 3 Season 4 was announced on November 18 at the Pro League Season 8 Finals in Rio de Janeiro and was set in Morocco.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.trueachievements.com/n35166/rainbow-six-siege-year-3-season-4-details-take-siege-in-morocco|title=Rainbow Six Siege Year 3 Season 4 Details Take Siege In Morocco|work=[[TrueAchievements]]|access-date=November 13, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114060216/https://www.trueachievements.com/n35166/rainbow-six-siege-year-3-season-4-details-take-siege-in-morocco|archive-date=November 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2018/11/257583/rainbow-six-siege-game-feature-moroccan-scenes/|title=Tom Clancy\u2019s \u2018Rainbow Six Siege\u2019 Game to Feature Moroccan Scenes|date=November 12, 2018|work=[[Morocco World News]]|access-date=November 13, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113212442/https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2018/11/257583/rainbow-six-siege-game-feature-moroccan-scenes/|archive-date=November 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Six Invitational 2020, in February 2020, had the highest prize pool in all of Rainbow Six with $3,000,000 split among 16 teams, with the victors, Spacestation Gaming from North America, taking home the lion's share of $1,000,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/ubisofts-six-invitational-tournament-shows-why-publishers-like-esports.html|title=Ubisoft's $3 million tournament shows why game publishers are betting big on esports|last=Pei|first=Annie|date=2020-02-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217204424/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/ubisofts-six-invitational-tournament-shows-why-publishers-like-esports.html|archive-date=February 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Six Invitational 2020 also announce enormous changes to both the game itself and the competitive scene. The changes included the end of Pro League and a new points-based system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esportsobserver.com/r6-regionalization-structure/|title=Ubisoft Rolls Out Rainbow Six Siege Regionalization Structure|date=2020-02-16|website=The Esports Observer\uff5cthe world\u2019s leading source for essential esports business news and insights|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217204426/https://esportsobserver.com/r6-regionalization-structure/|archive-date=February 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> These changes to the competitive scene have been compared to that of ''Dota 2'' and [[League of Legends]].\n\n===Downloadable content===\n{{Excerpt|List of Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege downloadable content}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 79/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege |title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128163335/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege |archive-date=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><br />(XONE) 74/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege |title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151207010707/http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege |archive-date=December 7, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><br />(PS4) 73/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege |title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128002923/http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege |archive-date=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Destruct = 8/10<ref name=\"DestructRev\">{{cite web |last=Carter |first=Chris |date=December 2, 2015 |url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-tom-clancy-s-rainbow-six-siege-323032.phtml |title=Review: Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=December 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204075701/http://www.destructoid.com/review-tom-clancy-s-rainbow-six-siege-323032.phtml |archive-date=December 4, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"GIRev\">{{cite magazine |last=Bertz |first=Matt |date=December 4, 2015 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/rainbow_six_siege/b/pc/archive/2015/12/04/game-informer-rainbow-six-siege-review.aspx |title=A Slimmed-Down Combatant Struggles With The Weight Of Expectation - Rainbow Six: Siege - PC |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=December 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214225815/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/rainbow_six_siege/b/pc/archive/2015/12/04/game-informer-rainbow-six-siege-review.aspx |archive-date=February 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"GameRevRev\">{{cite web |last=Leack |first=Jonathan |date=December 8, 2015 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/69596-tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege-review#/slide/1 |title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six: Siege Review |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=December 8, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711134646/http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/69596-tom-clancys-rainbow-six-siege-review#/slide/1 |archive-date=July 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"GSpotRev\">{{cite web |last=Butterworth |first=Scott |date=December 4, 2015 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rainbow-six-siege-review/1900-6416324/ |title=Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=December 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208025000/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rainbow-six-siege-review/1900-6416324/ |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadarRev\">{{cite web |last=Griffin |first=Ben |date=November 30, 2015 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/rainbow-six-siege-review/ |title=Rainbow Six: Siege review |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212152957/http://www.gamesradar.com/rainbow-six-siege-review/ |archive-date=December 12, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.5/10<ref name=\"IGNRev2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/18/rainbow-six-siege-review-3|title=Rainbow Six Siege Review 2018|first=Tom|last=Marks|work=[[IGN]]|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502133215/https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/18/rainbow-six-siege-review-3|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><br><s>7.9/10</s><ref name=\"IGNRev\">{{cite web |last=McCaffrey |first=Ryan |date=November 30, 2015 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/11/30/rainbow-six-siege-review |title=Rainbow Six Siege Review |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=November 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130200255/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/11/30/rainbow-six-siege-review |archive-date=November 30, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 90/100<ref name=\"PCGRev\">{{cite magazine |last=Davenport |first=James |date=December 3, 2015 |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-review/ |title=Rainbow Six Siege review |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=December 3, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203022829/http://www.pcgamer.com/rainbow-six-siege-review/ |archive-date=December 3, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Poly = 6/10<ref name=\"PolyRev\">{{cite web |last=Gies |first=Arthur |date=December 10, 2015 |url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/12/10/9888126/rainbow-six-siege-review |title=Rainbow Six Siege review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=December 10, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212012836/http://www.polygon.com/2015/12/10/9888126/rainbow-six-siege-review |archive-date=December 12, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| VG = 8/10<ref name=\"VGRev\">{{cite web |last=Burns |first=Steven |date=December 4, 2015 |url=http://www.videogamer.com/reviews/rainbow_six_siege_review.html |title=Rainbow Six Siege Review |work=VideoGamer.com |accessdate=December 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208065315/http://www.videogamer.com/reviews/rainbow_six_siege_review.html |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe pre-release reception of the game was positive, with critics praising the game's design and tensions created during matches.<ref name=\"GSpot tense\"/> In 2014, the game received four nominations from [[Game Critics Awards]]: Best of Show, Best PC Game, Best Action Game and Best Online Multiplayer Game.<ref name=\"E32014Noms\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/06/24/e3-2014-game-critics-awards-nominations-announced.aspx|title=E3 2014 Game Critics Awards Nominations Announced|first=Mike|last=Futter|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=June 24, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624195923/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/06/24/e3-2014-game-critics-awards-nominations-announced.aspx|archive-date=June 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The game eventually became the winner of the Best PC Game category.<ref name=\"E32014Winners\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2014winners.html|title=2014 Winners|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810110516/http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2014winners.html|archive-date=August 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege'' received \"generally favorable\" reviews from critics, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]]. Critics generally praised the game's destructive environment, tactical nature, map design, and its focus on teamwork. However, the lack of content and the game's microtransactions were subjected to criticism.\n\nThe game's multiplayer was widely praised by critics. Chris Carter from ''[[Destructoid]]'' praised the game's open-ended nature, which made each match unpredictable and helped the experience to stay fresh even after an extended period of playing.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> [[GameSpot]]'s Scott Butterworth appreciated the title for allowing players to make use of their creativity in approaching a mission.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> James Davenport from ''[[PC Gamer]]'' echoed this thought, and he described ''Siege'' as a \"psychological race\" in which players are constantly trying to outwit their opponents.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Ryan McCaffery from [[IGN]] also praised the tactical possibilities, which make the game \"tense and riveting\".<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> The large number of operators available for players to choose were praised by both Carter and Matt Bertz from ''[[Game Informer]]'', who commented that they added depths and variety to the game and that players could experiment to see which pairs of operators can complement each other.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> However, McCaffery was disappointed by the lack of variety of game modes and commented that most players usually neglect the mode's objectives and opted to simply eliminate their opponents.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> Terrorist Hunt received divisive opinions from critics. Carter thought that it was more relaxing,<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> and Butterworth thought it was exhilarating. However, Bertz criticized its lack of variety, weak [[Artificial intelligence (video games)|artificial intelligence]], and its less-intense nature when compared with the player-versus-player modes.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Martin Robinson from [[Eurogamer]] also noted that the mode only ran at 30 [[frames per second]], which limited its appeal.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-12-03-rainbow-six-siege-review|title=Rainbow Six Siege review: Six Pack|first=Martin|last=Robinson|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=December 3, 2015|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808040913/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-12-03-rainbow-six-siege-review|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game's focus on tactics was praised. Bertz applauded the tactical nature of the game, as it fostered communications between players. However, he noted that teamwork may not be possible if players did not have a headphone and microphone.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Arthur Gies from ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' echoed these comments, stating that the game's over-reliance on teamwork meant that when teammates were not communicating, the game would not be fun to play.<ref name=\"PolyRev\"/> The \"No Respawn\" system was praised by Butterworth for making each match feel intense, as even the best player needs to think tactically in order to win.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Jonathon Leack from [[Game Revolution]] enjoyed the scouting phase of a multiplayer match, which encouraged players to communicate with each other and coordinate their attacks.<ref name=\"GameRevRev\"/> However, Gies noted that the placement of game objectives does not vary much, thus making the scouting phase meaningless. Both Bertz and Butterworth agreed that the game's competitive nature increases the game's replay value.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Ben Griffin from [[GamesRadar]] praised the destruction mechanic for bringing tactical depth to the game.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/>\n\nThe gameplay received mixed reviews. Both Bertz and Griffin criticized the game's incompetent hit detection system, which made the experience unfair.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Bertz described the game's gunplay as \"serviceable\",<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> while Leack noticed a delay in shooting, which drags the game's pace and leads to a steep learning curve. However, Leack appreciated the game's map design, which opened many possibilities. He also praised its attention to detail and sound design, which can often make a multiplayer match feel like a \"great action film\".<ref name=\"GameRevRev\"/> Bertz was disappointed by the lack of customization options, which did not offer long-term progression for the players.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Butterworth similarly criticized the progression system for being slow. As players cannot play as the same operator in the same match, he was often forced to play as the generic \"recruit\" character when he was only at the beginning stage of the game. He also criticized the limited weapon customization options, which barely affect gameplay.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> McCaffery described customization as the \"least interesting\" aspect of the game and claimed that most gameplay features were locked when players started playing.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> Griffin, Gies, and Steven Burns from ''VideoGamer.com'' were annoyed by the [[microtransaction]]s featured in the game,<ref name=\"VGRev\"/><ref name=\"PolyRev\"/> with Griffin describing it as a greedy attempt by Ubisoft to make more money,<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> though Davenport did not mind these features as they were limited to cosmetic items and could be unlocked through earning Renown.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Bertz was annoyed the lack of clan infrastructure, which may cause players troubles when they were finding matches,<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> while Griffin thought that map rotation often felt random and was disappointed that players cannot vote to decide which map they are going to play next.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/>\n\nSingle-player was generally considered a disappointment by critics, with Situations receiving mixed reviews. Carter described it as one of his \"favorite non-campaign additions\" as the mode gave players incentive to return due to its rating system. Butterworth described it as a \"surprisingly robust\" mode and thought that there were great tutorial missions that help players to understand gameplay before trying multiplayer.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> However, Bertz criticized it for its lack of replay value,<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> and Griffin noted their short length.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> McCaffery thought that it served as a competent tutorial, but its solo play nature meant that players could not practice team play and tactics.<ref name=\"IGNRev\"/> Davenport criticized the narrative in Situations, which he thought was not meaningful.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Many critics were disappointed with the lack of a single-player campaign or a cooperative campaign,<ref name=\"GIRev\"/><ref name=\"GameRevRev\"/> but Butterworth believed that the strong multiplayer components can compensate for this absence.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Gies noticed certain network issues would affect the single-player.<ref name=\"PolyRev\"/>\n\nMany critics generally had a positive opinion on the package. Bertz thought that the game's multiplayer design had laid a great foundation for the game, but it was not taken advantage of due to the small number of game modes.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/> Leack felt that ''Siege''{{'}}s tight focus on tactical gameplay had \"provided something unlike any other game on the market\".<ref name=\"GameRevRev\"/> Butterworth found the game very unique and that there was \"nothing else like it\" when he put aside the game's minor annoyances.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Griffin wrote that the title felt very fresh, as most games in the market did not value tactics.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Davenport similarly praised the game for being very concentrated and making no compromises on gameplay design, which in turn make the title one of the best tactical multiplayer shooters on the market.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Gies recognized the game's potential but thought that they were overshadowed by the game's numerous technical annoyances, frustrating progression system and its lack of content.<ref name=\"PolyRev\"/> Robinson was impressed by the game's multiplayer mode, and that the overall package could be considered as the year's best multiplayer game. However, he questioned Ubisoft for releasing the game with so little content while still selling it at full-price.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/>\n\n===Games as a service===\nIn May 2015, CEO of Ubisoft Yves Guillemot announced that the company expected the game to outsell {{nowrap|''[[Far Cry 4]]''}}'s seven million sales over the course of its lifetime because of post-launch support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/12/ubisoft-updating-rainbow-six-siege-for-a-long-time?|title=Ubisoft Updating Rainbow Six Siege 'For a Long Time'|first=Mitch|last=Dyer|date=May 12, 2015|accessdate=May 14, 2015|work=[[IGN]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514235646/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/12/ubisoft-updating-rainbow-six-siege-for-a-long-time|archivedate=May 14, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the game's launch, it debuted at number six in UK Software Charts, selling 76,000 retail copies across all three platforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/manifesto/rainbow-six-siege-isnt-selling-well-and-it-deserves-better-35665|title=Rainbow Six Siege Isn't Selling Well, and It Deserves Better|publisher=[[Game Revolution]]|first=Jonathan|last=Leack|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=December 9, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209160412/http://www.gamerevolution.com/manifesto/rainbow-six-siege-isnt-selling-well-and-it-deserves-better-35665|archivedate=December 9, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Critics thought that the launch performance was underwhelming and lacklustre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/12/07/just-cause-3-and-rainbow-six-siege-underwhelm-in-uk-charts-5549119/|title=Just Cause 3 and Rainbow Six Siege underwhelm in UK charts|work=[[GameCentral]]|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806223731/http://metro.co.uk/2015/12/07/just-cause-3-and-rainbow-six-siege-underwhelm-in-uk-charts-5549119/|archive-date=August 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> However, through continued post-release support and updates, the player base had doubled since the game's launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/10/more-people-are-playing-rainbow-six-siege-now-than-at-launch|title=More People Are Playing Rainbow Six Siege Now Than At Launch|first=Vince|last=Ingenito|work=[[IGN]]|date=August 10, 2016|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606163103/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/10/more-people-are-playing-rainbow-six-siege-now-than-at-launch|archive-date=June 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the summer 2016 launch of the third DLC, ''Skull Rain'', the size of the player base had a 40% increase, and the title had more than 10 million registered players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/hows-ubisoft-doing-here-are-the-key-takeaways-from/1100-6445079/|title=How's Ubisoft Doing? Here Are the Key Takeaways From Latest Earnings Report|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=November 3, 2016|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806221925/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/hows-ubisoft-doing-here-are-the-key-takeaways-from/1100-6445079/|archive-date=August 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Two years after launch<!--May 2015 to May 2017-->, the game remained as one of the top 40 best-selling retail games in the UK.<ref name=\"postmortem\"/> The strong performance of ''Siege'', alongside with ''[[Tom Clancy's The Division]]'' (2016) and ''[[Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Wildlands]]'' (2017) boosted the total number of players of the ''[[Tom Clancy's]]'' franchise to 44 million in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/05/16/tom-clancy-games-have-44m-players-thanks-to-the-division-wildlands-rainbow-six-siege/|title=Tom Clancy games have 44M players thanks to The Division, Wildlands, Rainbow Six Siege|first=Stephen|last=Nunneley|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017|work=[[VG 247]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619174048/http://www.vg247.com/2017/05/16/tom-clancy-games-have-44m-players-thanks-to-the-division-wildlands-rainbow-six-siege/|archive-date=June 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2017, Ubisoft announced that the game had passed 20 million players and that the game was played by 2.3 million players every day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/08/05/rainbow-six-siege-has-20m-registered-players-and-2-3m-play-everyday/|title=Rainbow Six Siege has 20M registered players and 2.3M play everyday|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|work=[[VG 247]]|date=August 5, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206221626/https://www.vg247.com/2017/08/05/rainbow-six-siege-has-20m-registered-players-and-2-3m-play-everyday/|archive-date=December 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Two years after the game's launch, Ubisoft announced that the game has passed 25 million registered players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-12-06-rainbow-six-siege-hits-25-million-players-as-operation-white-noise-launches|title=Rainbow Six Siege hits 25 million players as Operation White Noise launches|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206202256/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-12-06-rainbow-six-siege-hits-25-million-players-as-operation-white-noise-launches|archive-date=December 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> As of February 2019, the game had more than 45 million registered players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/02/14/rainbow-six-siege-continues-to-drive-ubisofts-growth/|title=Rainbow Six: Siege continues to drive Ubisoft\u2019s growth|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=February 14, 2019|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183426/https://venturebeat.com/2019/02/14/rainbow-six-siege-continues-to-drive-ubisofts-growth/|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCritics agreed that while the game suffered a rocky launch, Ubisoft's efforts in updating the game and fixing bugs have increased the game's quality and had transformed the game into a better experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/5-best-evolving-multiplayer-games-in-2018/1100-6463768/|title=5 Best Evolving Multiplayer Games In 2018|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=December 17, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183436/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/5-best-evolving-multiplayer-games-in-2018/1100-6463768/|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-11-how-rainbow-six-siege-came-back-from-disaster-to-become-a-top-esport|title=How Rainbow Six Siege came back from disaster to become a top esport|first=Mike|last=Stubbs|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=September 11, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183433/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-11-how-rainbow-six-siege-came-back-from-disaster-to-become-a-top-esport|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/25/rainbow-six-siege-in-2019-whats-over-the-burnt-horizon|title=Rainbow Six Siege in 2019: What's Over the Burnt Horizon|first=Joab|last=Gilroy|work=[[IGN]]|date=March 25, 2019|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326143214/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/25/rainbow-six-siege-in-2019-whats-over-the-burnt-horizon|archive-date=March 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/2/19/17019772/rainbow-six-siege-roadmap-operators-esports|title=The redemption of Rainbow Six Siege|first=Taylor|last=Cocke|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=February 19, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183429/https://www.polygon.com/2018/2/19/17019772/rainbow-six-siege-roadmap-operators-esports|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[IGN]] and [[Eurogamer]] re-reviewed the game in 2018 and both concluded that the game had improved significantly since its launch.<ref name=\"IGNRev2018\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-29-rainbow-six-siege-re-review-an-exceptional-tactical-multiplayer-experience|title=Rainbow Six Siege re-review - an exceptional tactical multiplayer experience|first=Chris|last=Thursten|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 29, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406082306/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-29-rainbow-six-siege-re-review-an-exceptional-tactical-multiplayer-experience|archive-date=April 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Several years after the game's launch, ''Siege'' was regarded as one of the best multiplayer games released for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] by some critics, with praise being directed to its distinctiveness and the similarities it shares with [[multiplayer online battle arena]] games and [[hero shooter]]s.<ref name=\"GI Post\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/3256145/rainbow-six-siege-year-3.html|title=Entering year three, Rainbow Six Siege is still the only true \"next-gen\" shooter|first=Hayden|last=Dingman|work=[[PC World]]|date=February 17, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426184934/https://www.pcworld.com/article/3256145/rainbow-six-siege-year-3.html|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/08/29/rainbow-six-siege-return-to-the-game/|title=Joining the Siege: why now is a great time to return to Rainbow Six|first=Sam|last=Greer|work=[[VG 247]]|date=August 29, 2018|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183429/https://www.vg247.com/2018/08/29/rainbow-six-siege-return-to-the-game/|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Remy, the team focused on players retention in the year after the game's launch, but the growth of the game's player base exceeded their expectations. He called the game \"a testament\" to the [[games as a service]] model.<ref name=\"reboot\"/> Jeff Grubb from ''[[VentureBeat]]'' attributed ''Siege'''s high player retention rate and successful eSports events to Ubisoft's continuous and frequent updates to the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/11/07/rainbow-six-siege-quietly-captures-25-million-players/|title=Rainbow Six Siege quietly captures 25 million players|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=November 7, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183434/https://venturebeat.com/2017/11/07/rainbow-six-siege-quietly-captures-25-million-players/|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[GameSpot]] described ''Siege'' as \"one of modern [[AAA (video game industry)|AAA]] gaming's biggest comebacks\", and the best proof to show that the \"games-as-a-service\" model works well, attributing its success to Ubisoft's continuous updates and the thriving community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-astonishing-comeback/1100-6455698/|title=Rainbow Six Siege's Astonishing Comeback|first=Michael|last=McHardy|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216173937/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rainbow-six-sieges-astonishing-comeback/1100-6455698/|archive-date=December 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Haydn Taylor from ''[[Gameindustry.biz]]'' praised Ubisoft's monetization methods, which was less aggressive than other gaming companies like [[Electronic Arts]]. Unlike titles such as ''[[Star Wars Battlefront II (2017 video game)|Star Wars Battlefront II]]'' (2017), the game's monetization methods and the use of [[loot box]]es generated minimal amount of backlash from players. He added that Ubisoft had showed, with ''Siege'', \"the delicate and reasoned approach that's been missing from the industry's clumsy, heavy-handed adoption of the games-as-a-service model\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-12-06-what-rainbow-six-sieges-25-million-users-says-about-games-as-a-service|title=What reaching 25 million users says about Rainbow Six Siege and games-as-a-service|first=Haydn|last=Taylor|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426183429/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-12-06-what-rainbow-six-sieges-25-million-users-says-about-games-as-a-service|archive-date=April 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The post-launch success for ''Siege'' further solidified Ubisoft's belief in the model. Future Ubisoft multiplayer-focused titles \u2013 such as ''[[For Honor]]'' \u2013 adopted this structure, in which the company would provide free DLC and updates several years after the game's official release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2016-11-22-no-more-dlc-that-gamers-have-to-buy-for-the-full-experience-ubisoft|title=\"No more DLC that gamers have to buy for the full experience\" - Ubisoft|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607052524/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2016-11-22-no-more-dlc-that-gamers-have-to-buy-for-the-full-experience-ubisoft|archive-date=June 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\" | 2014\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best of Show\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"E32014Noms\"/><ref name=\"E32014Winners\"/>\n|-\n| Best PC Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Action Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\" | 2015\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Game Critics Awards\n| Best PC Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2015nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2015 (2015 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314055342/http://gamecriticsawards.com/2015nominees.html|archive-date=March 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Action Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Gamescom]] 2015\n| Best Online Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://loadscreen.com.au/2015/08/04/nominees-for-gamescom-2015-awards-announced/|title=Nominees for Gamescom 2015 awards announced|first=Tom|last=Heath|publisher=LoadScreen|date=August 4, 2015|accessdate=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316151835/http://loadscreen.com.au/2015/08/04/nominees-for-gamescom-2015-awards-announced/|archive-date=March 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]] 2016\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/golden-joystick-awards/news/a807943/golden-joystick-awards-2016-voting-now-open-to-the-public/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2016 voting now open to the public|first=Sam|last=Loveridge|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=September 15, 2016|accessdate=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228140939/http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/golden-joystick-awards/news/a807943/golden-joystick-awards-2016-voting-now-open-to-the-public/|archive-date=February 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2016]]\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegameawards.com/2016/winners/|title=The Game Awards 2016: 2016 Winners|publisher=[[The Game Awards]]|accessdate=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728063331/http://thegameawards.com/2016/winners/|archive-date=July 28, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]] 2017\n| Esports Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bestinslot.co/golden-joystick-awards-2017-nominees/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2017 Nominees|first=Eri|last=Gaito|publisher=Best in Slot|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110003232/https://www.bestinslot.co/golden-joystick-awards-2017-nominees/|archive-date=January 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2017]]\n| Best Ongoing Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2017-winners-headlined-by-zelda-br/1100-6455467/|title=The Game Awards 2017 Winners Headlined By Zelda: Breath Of The Wild's Game Of The Year|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=December 8, 2017|accessdate=December 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209043912/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2017-winners-headlined-by-zelda-br/1100-6455467/|archive-date=December 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"8\" | 2018\n| Italian Video Game Awards 2018\n| Radio 105 eSports Game of the Year\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://italianvideogameawards.com/awards|title=Italian Video Game Nominees and Winners 2018|publisher=Italian Video Game Awards|date=March 14, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321193010/https://italianvideogameawards.com/awards|archivedate=March 21, 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[14th British Academy Games Awards]]\n| Evolving Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/business/hellblade-senuas-sacrifice-at-forefront-of-bafta-games-awards-nominations|title=Hellblade: Senua's Sacrifice at forefront of BAFTA Games Awards nominations|first=Marie|last=deAlessandri|date=March 15, 2018|work=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]|accessdate=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316161255/https://www.mcvuk.com/business/hellblade-senuas-sacrifice-at-forefront-of-bafta-games-awards-nominations|archive-date=March 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/bafta-names-what-remains-of-edith-finch-its-best-game-of-2017-498392.phtml|title=BAFTA names What Remains of Edith Finch its best game of 2017|first=Brett|last=Makedonski|website=[[Destructoid]