\n*1975\u20131977: Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez\n*1977: [[Juan Hohberg]]\n*1977\u20131979: Ra\u00fal Bentancor\n||\n*1979\u20131982: [[Roque M\u00e1spoli]]\n*1982\u20131987: [[Omar Borr\u00e1s]]\n*1987\u20131988: [[Roberto Fleitas]]\n*1988\u20131990: [[\u00d3scar Tab\u00e1rez]]\n*1990\u20131993: [[Luis Cubilla]]\n*1993\u20131994: [[Ildo Maneiro]]\n*1994\u20131996: [[H\u00e9ctor N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]\n*1996\u20131997: Juan Ahuntcha\u00edn\n*1997\u20131998: [[Roque M\u00e1spoli]]\n*1998\u20132000: [[V\u00edctor P\u00faa]]\n*2000\u20132001: [[Daniel Passarella]]\n*2001\u20132003: [[V\u00edctor P\u00faa]]\n*2003: [[Gustavo Ferr\u00edn]]\n*2003\u20132004: [[Juan Ram\u00f3n Carrasco]]\n*2004\u20132006: [[Jorge Fossati]]\n*2006: [[Gustavo Ferr\u00edn]]\n*2006\u2013present: [[\u00d3scar Tab\u00e1rez]]\n||\n|}\n\n==Emblem==\n[[File:Uruguay - Costa Rica FIFA World Cup 2013 (2014-06-14; fans) 06.jpg|thumb|Uruguay national team fans at 2014 FIFA World Cup]]\nUruguay have 4 stars in the emblem, 2 stars from the Gold medals earned in the 1924 and 1928 Olympic Games (recognized by FIFA as World Championships in accordance with the IOC) and 2 stars from the two World Cups from 1930 and 1950.<ref>{{cite book|title=Or\u00edgenes de la Copa Mundial de la FIFA|url=http://es.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/ip-201_02s_fwc-origin_8819.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111130914/http://es.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/ip-201_02s_fwc-origin_8819.pdf|archivedate=11 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Rivalries==\n===Argentina===\n{{main|Argentina\u2013Uruguay football rivalry}}\nUruguay has a long-standing rivalry with [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], that came into existence when they beat their South American neighbors 4\u20132 in the [[1930 FIFA World Cup Final|first World Cup final]], held in [[Montevideo]] in 1930. As a response, the following day saw an angry mob threw stones at the Uruguayan consulate in the Argentinian capital [[Buenos Aires]].\n\n===Brazil===\n{{Main|Brazil\u2013Uruguay football rivalry}}\nUruguay has an old rivalry with their South American neighbors. Their best known match was played at the 1950 World Cup which was held in Brazil where they defeated the host with the result 2\u20131 in front of almost 200,000 spectators at the Maracan\u00e3 Stadium, thus winning the competition and earning their second World Cup title.\n\n==Honours==\nNote: Below is a list of achievements by the senior national team\n\n*'''[[FIFA World Cup]]''':\n** '''Champions (2):''' [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]], [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]]\n*** Fourth place: [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]], [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]], [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]]\n*'''[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]''':\n** Fourth place: [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup|1997]], [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013]]\n*'''[[Copa Am\u00e9rica|South American Championship / Copa Am\u00e9rica]]''':\n** '''Champions (15):''' [[1916 South American Championship|1916]], [[1917 South American Championship|1917]], [[1920 South American Championship|1920]], [[1923 South American Championship|1923]], [[1924 South American Championship|1924]], [[1926 South American Championship|1926]], [[1935 South American Championship|1935]], [[1942 South American Championship|1942]],{{refn|Extra edition|group=note|name=extra}} [[1956 South American Championship|1956]], [[1959 South American Championship (Ecuador)|1959 (Ecuador)]], [[1967 South American Championship|1967]], [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1983]], [[1987 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1987]], [[1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1995]], [[2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2011]]\n** Runners-up: [[1919 South American Championship|1919]], [[1927 South American Championship|1927]], [[1939 South American Championship|1939]], [[1941 South American Championship|1941]], [[1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1989]], [[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1999]]\n** Third place: [[1921 South American Championship|1921]], [[1922 South American Championship|1922]], [[1929 South American Championship|1929]], [[1937 South American Championship|1937]], [[1947 South American Championship|1947]], [[1953 South American Championship|1953]], [[1957 South American Championship|1957]], [[1975 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1975]], [[2004 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2004]]\n** Fourth place: [[1945 South American Championship|1945]], [[1946 South American Championship|1946]], [[1955 South American Championship|1955]], [[2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2001]], [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2007]]\n*'''[[Artemio Franchi Trophy]]''':\n** Runners-up: [[Artemio Franchi Trophy#1985|1985]]\n*'''[[Football at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]]''':\n** '''Gold medal (2):''' [[Football at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924]], [[Football at the 1928 Summer Olympics|1928]]\n*'''[[Football at the Pan American Games|Pan American Games]]'''\n** '''Gold medal (1):''' [[Football at the 1983 Pan American Games|1983]]\n** Fourth place: [[Football at the 1963 Pan American Games|1963]]\n*'''[[1980 Mundialito]]'''\n** '''Gold medal (1):''' [[1980 Mundialito|1981]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Association football|Uruguay}}\n* [[Uruguay national under-23 football team]]\n* [[Uruguay national under-20 football team]]\n* [[Uruguay national under-17 football team]]\n* [[Uruguay national futsal team]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Uruguay national football team}} \n* [http://www.auf.org.uy/Portal/SELECTIONS_MENS/1/ Official website] {{in lang|es}}\n* [https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=uru/ Uruguay FIFA profile]\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/uru-intres.html RSSSF archive of results 1902\u2013]\n\n{{Uruguay national football team}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Titles\n| bg    = gold\n| list1 =\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach|ach}}\n{{succession box\n |before = Inaugural Champions\n |title  = [[FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup Champions]]\n |years  = [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]] (1st title)\n |after  = [[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]] {{fb-rt|